§ Why ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ If we stack a rectangle on top of itself we have a
    rectangle twice the height. ⦉

  ‖ The additivity principle says that the area of the so-formed
    rectangle is the sum of the areas of the stacked rectangles. ⦉

  ‖ Our definition of integral for simple functions has this
    property. ⦉
⦉

§ Result ⦉
<statement type='proposition'>
  ‖ The simple non-negative integral operator is homogenous over
    non-negative real values. ⦉
</statement>
<proof>
  ‖ Let $(X, 𝒜, μ)$ be a measure space. ⦉

  ‖ Let $\SimpleF_+(X)$ denote the non-negative real-valued simple
    functions on $X$. ⦉

  ‖ Define $s: \SimpleF_+(X) → [0, ∈fty]$ by $s(f) = ∫f dμ$
    for $f ∈ \SimpleF_+(X)$. ⦉
  ¶ ⦊
    ‖ In this notation, we want to show that $s(α f) = α
      s(f)$ for all $α ∈ [0, ∈fty)$ and $f ∈ \SimpleF_+(X)$. ⦉

    ‖ Toward this end, let $f ∈ \SimpleF_+(X)$ with the simple
      partition $\set{A_n} ⊂ 𝒜$ and $\set{a_n} ⊂ [0, ∈fty]$. ⦉
  ⦉

